# COMPARISON TABLES

## Table 1: TCP vs UDP

| Feature | TCP | UDP |
|---------|-----|-----|
| Connection | Connection-oriented | Connectionless |
| Reliability | Guaranteed delivery | Best-effort |
| Ordering | Yes | No |
| Speed | Slower | Faster |
| Header | 20-60 bytes | 8 bytes |
| Flow control | Yes | No |
| Congestion control | Yes | No |
| Broadcast | No | Yes |
| Overhead | High | Low |
| Use | HTTP, FTP, SSH, Email | DNS, DHCP, Streaming, Gaming |

## Table 2: IPv4 vs IPv6

| Feature | IPv4 | IPv6 |
|---------|------|------|
| Size | 32-bit | 128-bit |
| Notation | Dotted decimal | Hex colon |
| Addresses | ~4.3 billion | ~3.4 × 10^38 |
| Header | Variable (20-60B) | Fixed (40B) |
| Checksum | Yes | No |
| NAT | Required | Not needed |
| IPSec | Optional | Mandatory |
| Broadcast | Yes | No (multicast instead) |
| Fragmentation | Routers & source | Source only |
| Configuration | Manual/DHCP | Auto (SLAAC) |

## Table 3: Hub vs Switch vs Router

| Feature | Hub | Switch | Router |
|---------|-----|--------|--------|
| Layer | 1 (Physical) | 2 (Data Link) | 3 (Network) |
| Addressing | None | MAC | IP |
| Intelligence | None | MAC table | Routing table |
| Broadcast domain | 1 | 1 (VLANs split) | Each port = 1 |
| Collision domain | 1 | Per port | Per port |
| Traffic | Floods all ports | Forwards to specific port | Routes between networks |
| Speed | Shared | Dedicated | Depends |
| Use | Obsolete | LAN | Inter-network |

## Table 4: HTTP vs HTTPS

| Feature | HTTP | HTTPS |
|---------|------|-------|
| Port | 80 | 443 |
| Security | None (plaintext) | TLS encrypted |
| Certificate | Not needed | Required (X.509) |
| Speed | Slightly faster | Slightly slower (TLS overhead) |
| SEO | Lower ranking | Higher ranking |
| Data integrity | No | Yes |
| Use | Internal/test only | Everything in production |

## Table 5: Go-Back-N vs Selective Repeat

| Feature | Go-Back-N | Selective Repeat |
|---------|-----------|-----------------|
| Sender window | 2^n - 1 | 2^(n-1) |
| Receiver window | 1 | 2^(n-1) |
| Retransmission | All from error | Only errored frame |
| Buffering at receiver | No | Yes |
| ACK type | Cumulative | Individual |
| Efficiency | Lower | Higher |
| Complexity | Simple | Complex |
| Best for | Low error rate | High error rate |

## Table 6: Circuit Switching vs Packet Switching

| Feature | Circuit Switching | Packet Switching |
|---------|------------------|------------------|
| Path | Dedicated, fixed | Dynamic, variable |
| Setup | Required (delay) | Not required |
| Resources | Reserved (may waste) | Shared (efficient) |
| Delay | Constant after setup | Variable per packet |
| Order | Guaranteed | May arrive out of order |
| Use | PSTN (telephone) | Internet |
| Billing | Duration-based | Data volume-based |
| Failure handling | Call drops | Packets reroute |

## Table 7: OSI vs TCP/IP

| Feature | OSI | TCP/IP |
|---------|-----|--------|
| Layers | 7 | 4 |
| Origin | ISO | DARPA |
| Nature | Theoretical | Practical |
| Approach | Model → Protocols | Protocols → Model |
| Session layer | Yes | Merged into Application |
| Presentation layer | Yes | Merged into Application |
| Strict boundaries | Yes | Flexible |
| Real-world use | Teaching | Internet |

## Table 8: Stateful vs Stateless

| Feature | Stateful | Stateless |
|---------|----------|-----------|
| Server stores client state? | Yes | No |
| Scalability | Harder (state migration) | Easier (any server works) |
| Crash recovery | Difficult | Easy (retry to any server) |
| Examples | TCP, FTP, SSH | HTTP, UDP, DNS, REST |
| Performance | Can be faster (cached state) | Slightly slower (resend context) |
| Load balancing | Needs sticky sessions | Simple round-robin |
| Memory usage | Higher | Lower |
